{"type":"message","id":"e2afa4be","parentId":"9c36cc7f","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:35:20.457Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So there's no `agents/` directory in the workspace. This means `sessionsDir = /home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main/agents/main/sessions` doesn't exist as a real directory. The `resolveSessionFile` function would fail to find any session files there (since the `readdir` would fail or return empty).\n\nBUT the fallback logic kicks in (point 7: \"fallback: 最新 .jsonl（非 reset，仅当前 session 自己）\"). So `sessionFile` would be the current session's jsonl (since there's no reset file in this non-existent directory).\n \nWait, but the session-summary hook actually wrote a summary file, so it must have found the session somehow. Let me trace through the logic again—with an undefined `workspaceDir`, the sessionsDir would be `$HOME/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions` instead, which is where the actual session files are located.\n\nWhen `findPreviousSessionFile` runs with no `sessionId` or `currentSessionFile`, it falls back to finding the latest reset file in that directory, which is `b1c0599e-...reset...`. The function returns this file path, and then `extractMessages` reads 80 lines from it (40 pairs of user/assistant messages), giving us the startup sequence and the /new trigger that started the session.\n\nBut the file only contains 39 lines total, so after filtering out system/command messages and removing the startup sequence, there's barely any meaningful conversation left to extract.\n\nLooking at the fallback summary function, it checks whether there are at least 50 characters of content or ephemeral entries available. If neither condition is met, it generates a default \"无会话内容\" (no session content) response instead. The hook checks `content.trim().length > 50 || hasEphemeral` to decide whether to generate a real summary or use the fallback. Since the previous session was just the /new trigger, there's no content, and `hasEphemeral` depends on whether that session key shows up in the ephemeral file—but the ephemeral at that time (Apr 14 05) might not have had this session's key.\n\nLet me trace through what session key was actually used. The previous session's reset file is `b1c0599e-...`, and the hook would have extracted its session key from the event's `previousSessionEntry.sessionId`, falling back to `event.sessionKey` if needed.\n\nLooking at the sessions.json, `agent:main:main` has sessionId `e6b3bbe2-7c8b-41d8-8a5d-38ac0dae4b63`, but that's the current session after the reset, not the previous one. The sessions.json was updated when the new session started, so it no longer contains the old session's information. I need to figure out what session key the old session was using before it got replaced.\n\nActually, let me step back. The reset file was found and a fallback summary was written to `2026-04-14-无会话内容.md` at 21:26. That means the hook ran and completed successfully. The bootstrap hook should have injected this file when the new session started at 21:27. The issue might be in how the bootstrap hook is loading the session summaries from disk—I should check that logic again.\n\nLooking at the bootstrap hook's filtering criteria, the `2026-04-14-无会话内容.md` file should match since it contains `<!-- summary-only -->` and is only 213 characters. But I'm noticing the file has a duplicate header (`# Session: 2026-04-14 13:26` appears twice), which seems odd and might be causing the issue.\n\nWhen the bootstrap hook reads this file, it extracts just the first 2000 characters and injects them as `memory/2026-04-14-无会话内容.md`. The SOUL.md mentions reading session summaries from the memory directory, but I need to verify whether bootstrapFiles actually gets passed to the LLM as context. Let me check the gateway configuration to see how bootstrap files are supposed to be injected.","thinkingSignature":"98021ad2eb7ea621c53f28e35f415fb8a25e5002cee6406a83f85a0aabe7e71f"},{"type":"