{"type":"message","id":"bb4fdb84","parentId":"c8f0eea6","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:35:37.262Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! There's a `memory-lancedb` plugin configured with auto-capture and auto-recall. This is a different memory system than the session-summary/bootstrap hooks. It uses LanceDB for storage.\n\nBut more importantly, I can see the workspace is `/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace` (not `/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main`).\n\nSo `event.context.workspaceDir` for the main agent would be `/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main` (since that's where the workspace files are).\n\nBut the session-summary hook uses `workspaceDir/agents/main/sessions` = `/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/main/agents/main/sessions`, which doesn't exist.\n \nWait, I need to reconsider the fallback logic. When `workspaceDir` is undefined, the hook constructs the sessions directory using the home directory path, which would actually be the correct location where session files are stored. So the hook should be able to find the sessions after all.\n\nBut then there's the bootstrap hook to consider—it's looking for session summaries in the workspace's memory directory, and the session-summary hook is writing them to `~/.openclaw/workspace/memory/`, so those should be accessible to the bootstrap hook as long as it's reading from the right workspace location.\n\nThe real question is whether the `agent:bootstrap` event actually fires after `/new` creates a fresh session, and whether `event.context.bootstrapFiles` is properly populated by the gateway so those injected files actually reach the LLM during the startup sequence.\n\nSince the gateway process runs in the background, I can't directly observe the event firing, so let me check the memory pipeline more directly to see if there's a signal or trace of what happened.","thinkingSignature":"cb58505a77c5019b2465575ed0c5853f56ec5c17550cfd61c70a788098603394"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_w4s